“There’s nothing you can do for me,” said my grandfather. “The doctors said I have three months left.” He was telling me this for the first time, in a calm, soft voice. It was my last visit with him before I moved across the country. He was very sick. I couldn’t stand to see him like that, so I held his hand and started to cry. He didn’t say anything, just held my hand back and looked into my eyes. He had always been a man of few words, but I could tell that he wanted to say something. Finally, he broke the silence. “You know, there’s a lot of things I want to do before I die,” he said. “There are so many things I still want to do.” I started to cry harder, because I could tell that he really wanted to do all of those things, but he wouldn’t get the chance. He had to go back to the hospital, and I knew that the next time I saw him, he would be dead. I had never seen anyone die before. I didn’t know how I was going to handle it. But I knew I was going to be there for him when he did. I had to be. When he died, I went to his house to help my mom clean up. I saw his cane leaning against the wall, and it made me sad. He always needed it to walk, but he never complained about it. It just helped him get around. Now he was gone. There was so much I wanted to say to him, but now I never would. I went into his room to see if there was anything I could do for him, and I saw a box on his nightstand. I picked it up and opened it, and it was full of old letters and pictures. It was like
